02:01:17.670 --> 02:01:21.300
if we're going to be
linking among databases?

02:01:21.300 --> 02:01:25.930 position:56%
Or are there ways to get around that
or should we think about that now?

02:01:25.930 --> 02:01:30.680
&gt;&gt; So it's come up a few
times today that, you know,

02:01:30.680 --> 02:01:35.070
will people do what you want them
to do and I think the challenge is

02:01:35.070 --> 02:01:39.470
that whenever I, I started this
initiative about nine years ago

02:01:39.470 --> 02:01:40.940
and I asked all my colleagues

02:01:40.940 --> 02:01:43.850
at the time what do you want
to see in this database?

02:01:43.850 --> 02:01:46.320
And basically they said,
put something up there

02:01:46.320 --> 02:01:48.890
because we don't really
know until we see something

02:01:48.890 --> 02:01:51.780
so that wasn't really particularly
helpful but I think you really need

02:01:51.780 --> 02:01:55.010
to start from a standard and
then what we have done is try

02:01:55.010 --> 02:01:58.570
to standardize the
approach of the open access,

02:01:58.570 --> 02:02:02.990
the standardized file formats,
extracted metadata, engaging people

02:02:02.990 --> 02:02:07.140
who are expert in different
instrument, but also then trying

02:02:07.140 --> 02:02:11.020
to make sure that the structure
is robust enough to add

02:02:11.020 --> 02:02:15.140
in addition fields when people
suddenly say wait a minute,

02:02:15.140 --> 02:02:18.050
there's another way of
describing this that we can now do,

02:02:18.050 --> 02:02:20.560
we have a new instrument,
can we add that in?

02:02:20.560 --> 02:02:23.700
